          "body": "The chapter ends in one verse of devastating theological weight (3:10): *When God saw their deeds, that they turned from their wicked way, then God relented concerning the calamity which He had declared He would bring upon them. And He did not do it.* Three theological clauses. First, *God saw their deeds* — divine assessment is based on actual moral response, not profession alone (cf. James 2:18). Second, *God relented* (*nacham*) — the same verb used of God in Genesis 6:6 (regretted making man) and Exodus 32:14 (relented from destroying Israel after Moses' intercession). The doctrine here is what theologians call *conditional prophecy* — God's announcements of judgment are real warnings that anticipate repentance, as Jeremiah 18:7-10 makes explicit: *at one moment I might speak concerning a nation... to pluck up... but if that nation... turns from its evil, I will relent concerning the calamity I had planned.* Third, *He did not do it* — the chapter's final clause, a flat declaration that God's prophetic threat was withdrawn. This does not make God a liar (chapter 4 will probe the question); it reveals that the threat was always an invitation. Calvin notes: *God's threats are not absolute decrees, but means to bring sinners to repentance, that calamity may be averted.* Spurgeon: *the rope of mercy was let down into the deepest pit of Nineveh, and the city seized it with both hands.* The chapter closes with the verb of relenting — and chapter 4 opens with Jonah's anger at exactly the same word."
